      <title>18th century books looked like smartphones</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/2014/06/18th-century-books-looked-like-smartphones/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 08 Jun 2014 00:00:00 UTC</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/2014/06/18th-century-books-looked-like-smartphones/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Liked this picture of an 18th century book &lt;cite&gt;Conjectures on Original Composition&lt;/cite&gt; by Edward Young:&lt;figure class=&#34;figure aligncenter&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;http://leonpaternoster.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/small-book.gif&#34; alt=&#34;A narrow 18th century book&#34; width=&#34;399&#34; height=&#34;629&#34; /&gt;&lt;figcaption class=&#34;secondary&#34;&gt;From &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.collisiondetection.net/mt/archives/2014/02/_thats_one_of_t.php&#34;&gt;Collision Detection&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;
It shows how resilient we are as readers – we can deal with any ‘difficult’ measure. Another possible similarity between now and then is the sheer &lt;em&gt;mass&lt;/em&gt; of the stuff we&amp;#8217;re publishing; a fact plenty will bemoan, but I rather like this democratic, unpretentious fecundity (he said, pretentiously…) Also chimes with &lt;a href=&#34;http://leonpaternoster.com/2011/01/short-attention-spans-mobile-phones-and-the-future-of-reading/&#34; title=&#34;Short attention spans, mobile phones and the future of reading&#34;&gt;something I wrote many moons ago&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
